# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dynamodb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Werner Vogels, CTO at Amazon.com, provided a motivation for the project in his 2012 announcement.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon began as a decentralized network of services.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Originally, services had direct access to each other's databases.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When this became a bottleneck on engineering operations, services moved away from this direct access pattern in favor of public-facing APIs.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Still, third-party relational database management systems struggled to handle Amazon's client base.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] This culminated during the 2004 holiday season, when several technologies failed under high traffic.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Traditional databases often split data into smaller pieces to save space, but combining those pieces during searches can make queries slower.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Many of Amazon's services demanded mostly primary-key reads on their data, and with speed a top priority, putting these pieces together was extremely taxing.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Content with compromising storage efficiency, Amazon's response was Dynamo: a highly available key–value store built for internal use.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Dynamo, it seemed, was everything their engineers needed, but adoption lagged.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon's developers opted for "just works" design patterns with S3 and SimpleDB.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] While these systems had noticeable design flaws, they did not demand the overhead of provisioning hardware and scaling and re-partitioning data.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon's next iteration of NoSQL technology, DynamoDB, automated these database management operations.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB organizes data into tables, which are similar to spreadsheets.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each table contains items (rows), and each item is made up of attributes (columns).
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each item has a unique identifier called a primary key, which helps locate it within the table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A DynamoDB Table is a logical grouping of items, which represent the data stored in this Table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Given the NoSQL nature of DynamoDB, the Tables do not require that all items in a Table conform to some predefined schema.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] An Item in DynamoDB is a set of attributes that can be uniquely identified in a Table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] An Attribute is an atomic data entity that in itself is a Key-Value pair.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The Key is always of String type, while the value can be of one of multiple data types.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] An Item is uniquely identified in a Table using a subset of its attributes called Keys.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A Primary Key is a set of attributes that uniquely identifies items in a DynamoDB Table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Creation of a DynamoDB Table requires definition of a Primary Key.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each item in a DynamoDB Table is required to have all of the attributes that constitute the Primary Key, and no two items in a Table can have the same Primary Key.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Primary Keys in Dynamo DB can consist of either one or two attributes.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a Primary Key is made up of only one attribute, it is called a Partition Key.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Partition Keys determine the physical location of the associated item.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In this case, no two items in a table can have the same Partition Key.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a Primary Key is made up of two attributes, the first one is called a "Partition Key" and the second is called a "Sort Key".
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] As before, the Partition Key decides the physical Location of Data, but the Sort Key then decides the relative logical position of associated item's record inside that physical location.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In this case, two items in a Table can have the same Partition Key, but no two items in a partition can have the same Sort Key.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In other words, a given combination of Partition Key and Sort Key is guaranteed to have at most one item associated with it in a DynamoDB Table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB supports numerical, String, Boolean, Document, and Set Data Types.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Primary Key of a Table is the Default or Primary Index of a DynamoDB Table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In addition, a DynamoDB Table can have Secondary Indices.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A Secondary Index is defined on an attribute that is different from Partition Key or Sort Key as the Primary Index.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a Secondary Index has same Partition Key as Primary Index but a different Sort Key, it is called as the Local Secondary Index.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When Primary Index and Secondary Index have different Partition Key, the Secondary index is known as the Global Secondary Index.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB data modeling patterns are architectural approaches used in Amazon DynamoDB, a NoSQL database service designed for distributed systems.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] As well as "Time-Series Design", optimized for workloads like logging and metrics, typically using a partition key for entity identification and a sort key representing timestamps to efficiently query time-based datasets.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each pattern addresses specific technical requirements.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Single Table Design" can optimize query efficiency by co-locating related data under the same partition key to reduce access latency.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Multiple Table Design" enables separation of concerns by isolating data into purpose-specific tables with distinct access patterns.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Event Sourcing" preserves a historical log of state changes, often implemented with immutable data storage.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Materialized Views" simplify complex analytical queries through pre-aggregation strategies tailored to access patterns.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Time-Series Design" uses partitioning and sorting strategies to efficiently store and query large volumes of temporal data.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon DynamoDB's claim of single-digit millisecond latency primarily applies to simple operations such as `GetItem` and `PutItem`, which retrieve or modify individual items using their primary keys.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] This reflects the average latency under ideal conditions, such as even partition distribution and sufficient throughput provisioning, and does not account for transport overhead incurred during communication with the DynamoDB endpoint.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] More complex operations, such as `Query` with filters, `Scan`, or those involving large datasets, may experience increased latency due to additional computation and data transfer requirements.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Although DynamoDB does not natively support locking, different mechanisms exist.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Optimistic locking may use a version number to detect conflicts that occur after updates, rather than preventing them in advance.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Pessimistic locking, by contrast, may involve conditional updates with attributes such as `lockTime` and `lockedBy`.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When combined with Time to Live (TTL), these attributes enable the automated removal of expired locks, potentially enhancing concurrency management in event-driven architectures.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB uses hashing and B-trees to manage data.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Upon entry, data is first distributed into different partitions by hashing on the partition key.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each partition can store up to 10 GB of data and handle by default 1,000 write capacity units (WCU) and 3,000 read capacity units (RCU).
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] One RCU represents one strongly consistent read per second or two eventually consistent reads per second for items up to 4 KB in size.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] One WCU represents one write per second for an item up to 1 KB in size.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] To prevent data loss, DynamoDB features a two-tier backup system of replication and long-term storage.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each partition features three nodes, each of which contains a copy of that partition's data.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each node also contains two data structures: a B tree used to locate items, and a replication log that notes all changes made to the node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB periodically takes snapshots of these two data structures and stores them for a month in S3 so that engineers can perform point-in-time restores of their databases.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Within each partition, one of the three nodes is designated the "leader node".
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] All write operations travel first through the leader node before propagating, which makes writes consistent in DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] To maintain its status, the leader sends a "heartbeat" to each other node every 1.5 seconds.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Should another node stop receiving heartbeats, it can initiate a new leader election.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB uses the Paxos algorithm to elect leaders.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon engineers originally avoided Dynamo due to engineering overheads like provisioning and managing partitions and nodes.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In response, the DynamoDB team built a service it calls AutoAdmin to manage a database.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] AutoAdmin replaces a node when it stops responding by copying data from another node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a partition exceeds any of its three thresholds (RCU, WCU, or 10 GB), AutoAdmin will automatically add additional partitions to further segment the data.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Just like indexing systems in the relational model, DynamoDB demands that any updates to a table be reflected in each of the table's indices.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB handles this using a service it calls the "log propagator", which subscribes to the replication logs in each node and sends additional Put, Update, and Delete requests to indices as necessary.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Because indices result in substantial performance hits for write requests, DynamoDB allows a user at most five of them on any given table.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Suppose that a DynamoDB user issues a write operation (a Put, Update, or Delete).
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] While a typical relational system would convert the SQL query to relational algebra and run optimization algorithms, DynamoDB skips both processes.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] There are three nodes within, each with a copy of the partition's data.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The system first writes to the leader node, then writes to a second node, then sends a "success" message, and finally continues propagating to the third node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Writes are consistent because they always travel first through the leader node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Finally, the log propagator propagates the change to all indices.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] For each index, it grabs that index's primary key value from the item, then performs the same write on that index without log propagation.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] If the operation is an Update to a preexisting item, the updated attribute may serve as a primary key for an index, and thus the B tree for that index must update as well.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] B trees only handle insert, delete, and read operations, so in practice, when the log propagator receives an Update operation, it issues both a Delete operation and a Put operation to all indices.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Now suppose that a DynamoDB user issues a Get operation.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The request router proceeds as before with authentication and authorization.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Next, as above, we hash our partition key to arrive in the appropriate hash.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Now, we encounter a problem: with three nodes in eventual consistency with one another, how can we decide which to investigate?
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB offers the user two options when issuing a read: consistent and eventually consistent.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A consistent read visits the leader node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] But the consistency-availability trade-off rears its head again here: in read-heavy systems, always reading from the leader can overwhelm a single node and reduce availability.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The second option, an eventually consistent read, selects a random node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In practice, this is where DynamoDB trades consistency for availability.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] If we take this route, what are the odds of an inconsistency?
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] We'd need a write operation to return "success" and begin propagating to the third node, but not finish.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] We'd also need our Get to target this third node.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] This means a 1-in-3 chance of inconsistency within the write operation's propagation window.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Any number of catastrophes could cause a node to fall behind, but in the vast majority of cases, the third node is up-to-date within milliseconds of the leader.
[src:dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A race condition in a DynamoDB component triggered a 14 hour outage for Amazon's US-EAST-1 region on 19 October 2025, resulting in widespread outages of global services.
[src:dynamodb/dynamo-storage-system] Amazon DynamoDB is "built on the principles of Dynamo" and is a hosted service within the AWS infrastructure.
[src:dynamodb/dynamo-storage-system] However, while Dynamo is based on leaderless replication, DynamoDB uses single-leader replication.
[src:dynamodb/dynamo-storage-system] Amazon published the paper on Dynamo, but never released its implementation.
[src:dynamodb/dynamo-storage-system] The index layer of Amazon S3 implements and extends many core features of Dynamo.
[src:dynamodb/dynamo-storage-system] Since then, several implementations have been created based on the paper.
[src:dynamodb/dynamo-storage-system] The paper also inspired many other NoSQL database implementations, such as Apache Cassandra, Project Voldemort and Riak.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Amazon DynamoDB stores data in partitions.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] A *partition* is an allocation of storage for a table, backed by solid state drives (SSDs) and automatically replicated across multiple Availability Zones within an AWS Region.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Partition management is handled entirely by DynamoDB—you never have to manage partitions yourself.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] When you create a table, the initial status of the table is `CREATING`.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] During this phase, DynamoDB allocates sufficient partitions to the table so that it can handle your provisioned throughput requirements.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] You can begin writing and reading table data after the table status changes to `ACTIVE`.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Partition management occurs automatically in the background and is transparent to your applications.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Your table remains available throughout and fully supports your provisioned throughput requirements.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] For more details, see Partition key design.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Global secondary indexes in DynamoDB are also composed of partitions.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] The data in a global secondary index is stored separately from the data in its base table, but index partitions behave in much the same way as table partitions.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] If your table has a simple primary key (partition key only), DynamoDB stores and retrieves each item based on its partition key value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To write an item to the table, DynamoDB uses the value of the partition key as input to an internal hash function.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] The output value from the hash function determines the partition in which the item will be stored.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To read an item from the table, you must specify the partition key value for the item.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] DynamoDB uses this value as input to its hash function, yielding the partition in which the item can be found.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] The following diagram shows a table named *Pets*, which spans multiple partitions.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] The table's primary key is *AnimalType* (only this key attribute is shown).
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] DynamoDB uses its hash function to determine where to store a new item, in this case based on the hash value of the string *Dog*.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Note that the items are not stored in sorted order.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Each item's location is determined by the hash value of its partition key.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] DynamoDB is optimized for uniform distribution of items across a table's partitions, no matter how many partitions there may be.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] We recommend that you choose a partition key that can have a large number of distinct values relative to the number of items in the table.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] If the table has a composite primary key (partition key and sort key), DynamoDB calculates the hash value of the partition key in the same way as described in Data distribution: Partition key.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] However, it tends to keep items which have the same value of partition key close together and in sorted order by the sort key attribute's value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] The set of items which have the same value of partition key is called an item collection.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Item collections are optimized for efficient retrieval of ranges of the items within the collection.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] If your table doesn't have local secondary indexes, DynamoDB will automatically split your item collection over as many partitions as required to store the data and to serve read and write throughput.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To write an item to the table, DynamoDB calculates the hash value of the partition key to determine which partition should contain the item.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] In that partition, several items could have the same partition key value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] So DynamoDB stores the item among the others with the same partition key, in ascending order by sort key.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To read an item from the table, you must specify its partition key value and sort key value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] DynamoDB calculates the partition key's hash value, yielding the partition in which the item can be found.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] You can read multiple items from the table in a single operation (`Query`) if the items you want have the same partition key value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] DynamoDB returns all of the items with that partition key value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Optionally, you can apply a condition to the sort key so that it returns only the items within a certain range of values.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Suppose that the *Pets* table has a composite primary key consisting of *AnimalType* (partition key) and *Name* (sort key).
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] The following diagram shows DynamoDB writing an item with a partition key value of *Dog* and a sort key value of *Fido*.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To read that same item from the *Pets* table, DynamoDB calculates the hash value of *Dog*, yielding the partition in which these items are stored.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] DynamoDB then scans the sort key attribute values until it finds *Fido*.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To read all of the items with an *AnimalType* of *Dog*, you can issue a `Query` operation without specifying a sort key condition.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] By default, the items are returned in the order that they are stored (that is, in ascending order by sort key).
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] Optionally, you can request descending order instead.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] To query only some of the *Dog* items, you can apply a condition to the sort key (for example, only the *Dog* items where *Name* begins with a letter that is within the range `A` through `K`).
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] In a DynamoDB table, there is no upper limit on the number of distinct sort key values per partition key value.
[src:dynamodb/howitworks-partitions] If you needed to store many billions of *Dog* items in the *Pets* table, DynamoDB would allocate enough storage to handle this requirement automatically.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Amazon DynamoDB is a serverless, fully managed, distributed NoSQL database with single-digit millisecond performance at any scale.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB addresses your needs to overcome scaling and operational complexities of relational databases.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB is purpose-built and optimized for operational workloads that require consistent performance at any scale.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For example, DynamoDB delivers consistent single-digit millisecond performance for a shopping cart use case, whether you have 10 or 100 million users.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Launched in 2012, DynamoDB continues to help you move away from relational databases while reducing cost and improving performance at scale.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Customers across all sizes, industries, and geographies use DynamoDB to build modern, serverless applications that can start small and scale globally.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB scales to support tables of virtually any size while providing consistent single-digit millisecond performance and high availability.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For events, such as Amazon Prime Day, DynamoDB powers multiple high-traffic Amazon properties and systems, including Alexa, Amazon.com sites, and all Amazon fulfillment centers.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For such events, DynamoDB APIs have handled trillions of calls from Amazon properties and systems.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB continuously serves hundreds of customers with tables that have peak traffic of over half a million requests per second.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It also serves hundreds of customers whose table sizes exceed 200 TB, and processes over one billion requests per hour.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With DynamoDB, you don't need to provision any servers, or patch, manage, install, maintain, or operate any software.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB provides zero downtime maintenance.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It has no versions (major, minor, or patch), and there are no maintenance windows.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB's on-demand capacity mode offers pay-as-you-go pricing for read and write requests so you only pay for what you use.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With on-demand, DynamoDB instantly scales up or down your tables to adjust for capacity and maintains performance with zero administration.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It also scales down to zero so you don't pay for throughput when your table doesn't have traffic and there are no cold starts.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] As a NoSQL database, DynamoDB is purpose-built to deliver improved performance, scalability, manageability, and flexibility compared to traditional relational databases.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] To support a wide variety of use cases, DynamoDB supports both key-value and document data models.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Unlike relational databases, DynamoDB doesn't support a JOIN operator.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] We recommend that you denormalize your data model to reduce database round trips and processing power needed to answer queries.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] As a NoSQL database, DynamoDB provides strong read consistency and ACID transactions to build enterprise-grade applications.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] As a fully managed database service, DynamoDB handles the undifferentiated heavy lifting of managing a database so that you can focus on building value for your customers.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It handles setup, configurations, maintenance, high availability, hardware provisioning, security, backups, monitoring, and more.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] This ensures that when you create a DynamoDB table, it's instantly ready for production workloads.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB constantly improves its availability, reliability, performance, security, and functionality without requiring upgrades or downtime.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB was purpose-built to improve upon the performance and scalability of relational databases to deliver single-digit millisecond performance at any scale.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] To achieve this scale and performance, DynamoDB is optimized for high-performance workloads and provides APIs that encourage efficient database usage.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It omits features that are inefficient and non-performing at scale, for example, JOIN operations.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB delivers consistent single-digit millisecond performance for your application, whether you have 100 or 100 million users.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB is ideal for use cases that require consistent performance at any scale with little to zero operational overhead.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] To learn more about how customers from different industries use DynamoDB, see Amazon DynamoDB Customers and This is My Architecture.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Global tables provide multi-active replication of your data across your chosen AWS Regions with 99.999% availability.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Global tables deliver a fully managed solution for deploying a multi-Region, multi-active database, without building and maintaining your own replication solution.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With global tables, you can specify the AWS Regions where you want the tables to be available.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB replicates ongoing data changes to all of these tables.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Your globally distributed applications can access data locally in your selected Regions to achieve single-digit millisecond read and write performance.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Because global tables are multi-active, you don't need a primary table.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] This means there are no complicated or delayed fail-overs, or database downtime when failing over an application between Regions.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB is built for mission-critical workloads.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It includes (ACID) transactions support for applications that require complex business logic.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB provides native, server-side support for transactions, simplifying the developer experience of making coordinated, all-or-nothing changes to multiple items within and across tables.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB supports streaming of item-level change data capture (CDC) records in near-real time.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] It offers two streaming models for CDC: DynamoDB Streams and Kinesis Data Streams for DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Whenever an application creates, updates, or deletes items in a table, streams records a time-ordered sequence of every item-level change in near-real time.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] This makes DynamoDB Streams ideal for applications with event-driven architecture to consume and act upon the changes.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB offers the option to create both global and local secondary indexes, which let you query the table data using an alternate key.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With these secondary indexes, you can access data with attributes other than the primary key, giving you maximum flexibility in accessing your data.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB broadly integrates with several AWS services to help you get more value from your data, eliminate undifferentiated heavy lifting, and operate your workloads at scale.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Some examples are: AWS CloudFormation, Amazon CloudWatch, Amazon S3, AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM), and AWS Auto Scaling.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] To build end-to-end serverless applications, DynamoDB integrates natively with a number of serverless AWS services.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For example, you can integrate DynamoDB with AWS Lambda to create triggers, which are pieces of code that automatically respond to events in DynamoDB Streams.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With triggers, you can build event-driven applications that react to data modifications in DynamoDB tables.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For cost optimization, you can filter events that Lambda processes from a DynamoDB stream.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Integrating DynamoDB with Amazon S3 enables you to easily export data to an Amazon S3 bucket for analytics and machine learning.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB supports full table exports and incremental exports to export changed, updated, or deleted data between a specified time period.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You can also import data from Amazon S3 into a new DynamoDB table.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB supports zero-ETL integration with Amazon Redshift and Using an OpenSearch Ingestion pipeline with Amazon DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] These integrations enable you to run complex analytics and use advanced search capabilities on your DynamoDB table data.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For example, you can perform full-text and vector search, and semantic search on your DynamoDB data.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Zero-ETL integrations have no impact on production workloads running on DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) is a fully managed, highly available caching service built for DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DAX delivers up to 10 times performance improvement – from milliseconds to microseconds – even at millions of requests per second.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DAX does all the heavy lifting required to add in-memory acceleration to your DynamoDB tables, without requiring you to manage cache invalidation, data population, or cluster management.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB utilizes IAM to help you securely control access to your DynamoDB resources.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With IAM, you can centrally manage permissions that control which DynamoDB users can access resources.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You use IAM to control who is authenticated (signed in) and authorized (has permissions) to use resources.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Because DynamoDB utilizes IAM, there are no user names or passwords for accessing DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Because you don't have any complicated password rotation policies to manage, it simplifies your security posture.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With IAM, you can also enable fine-grained access control to provide authorization at the attribute level.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You can also define resource-based policies with support for IAM Access Analyzer and Block Public Access (BPA) to simplify policy management.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] By default, DynamoDB encrypts all customer data at rest.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Encryption at rest enhances the security of your data by using encryption keys stored in AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS).
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With encryption at rest, you can build security-sensitive applications that meet strict encryption compliance and regulatory requirements.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] When you access an encrypted table, DynamoDB decrypts the table data transparently.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You don't have to change any code or applications to use or manage encrypted tables.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB continues to deliver the same single-digit millisecond latency that you have come to expect, and all DynamoDB queries work seamlessly on your encrypted data.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You can specify whether DynamoDB should use an AWS owned key (default encryption type), AWS managed key, or a Customer managed key to encrypt user data.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] The default encryption using AWS-owned KMS keys is available at no additional charge.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For client-side encryption, you can use the AWS Database Encryption SDK.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB also adheres to several compliance standards, including HIPAA, PCI DSS, and GDPR, which enables you to meet regulatory requirements.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] By default, DynamoDB automatically replicates your data across three Availability Zones to provide high durability and a 99.99% availability SLA.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB also provides additional capabilities to help you achieve your business continuity and disaster recovery objectives.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB global tables enable a 99.999% availability SLA and multi-Region resilience.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] This helps you build resilient applications and optimize them for the lowest recovery time objective (RTO) and recovery point objective (RPO).
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Global tables also integrates with AWS Fault Injection Service (AWS FIS) to perform fault injection experiments on your global table workloads.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For example, pausing global table replication to any replica table.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Continuous backups provide you per-second granularity and the ability to initiate a point-in-time recovery.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With point-in-time recovery, you can restore a table to any point in time up to the second during the last 35 days.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You can set the recovery period to any value between 1 and 35 days.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Continuous backups and initiating a point-in-time restore doesn't use provisioned capacity.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] They also don't have any impact on the performance or availability of your applications.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] On-demand backup and restore let you create full backups of a table for long-term retention and archival for regulatory compliance needs.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Backups don't impact the performance of your table and you can back up tables of any size.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] With AWS Backup integration, you can use AWS Backup to schedule, copy, tag, and manage the life cycle of your DynamoDB on-demand backups automatically.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] Using AWS Backup, you can copy on-demand backups across accounts and Regions, and transition older backups to cold storage for cost-optimization.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You can work with DynamoDB using the AWS Management Console, the AWS Command Line Interface, NoSQL Workbench for DynamoDB, or DynamoDB APIs.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For more information, see Accessing DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB charges for reading, writing, and storing data in your tables, along with any optional features you choose to enable.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB has two capacity modes with their respective billing options for processing reads and writes on your tables: on-demand and provisioned.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] DynamoDB is also included in the **always free tier**, providing 25 GB of storage.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] The **Always free tier** also includes 25 provisioned Write and 25 provisioned Read Capacity Units (WCU, RCU) which is enough to handle 200 M requests per month.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For more information, see Amazon DynamoDB pricing.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] We also recommend that you review the following tutorials that present complete end-to-end procedures to familiarize yourself with DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] You can complete these tutorials using the **always free tier** feature.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] For information about resources, tools, and strategies to migrate to DynamoDB, see Migrating to DynamoDB.
[src:dynamodb/introduction] To read the latest blogs and whitepapers, see Amazon DynamoDB resources.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] A **quorum** is the minimum number of votes that a distributed transaction has to obtain in order to be allowed to perform an operation in a distributed system.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] A **quorum**-based technique is implemented to enforce consistent operation in a distributed system.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Quorum-based voting can be used as a replica control method, as well as a commit method to ensure transaction atomicity in the presence of network partitioning.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] In a distributed database system, a transaction could execute its operations at multiple sites.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Since atomicity requires every distributed transaction to be atomic, the transaction must have the same fate (commit or abort) at every site.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] In case of network partitioning, sites are partitioned and the partitions may not be able to communicate with each other.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] This is where a quorum-based technique comes in.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The fundamental idea is that a transaction is executed if the majority of sites vote to execute it.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Every site in the system is assigned a vote Vi.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Let us assume that the total number of votes in the system is V and the abort and commit quorums are Va and Vc, respectively.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Before a transaction commits, it must obtain a commit quorum Vc.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The total of at least one site that is prepared to commit and zero or more sites waiting $\geq$ Vc.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Before a transaction aborts, it must obtain an abort quorum Va The total of zero or more sites that are prepared to abort or any sites waiting $\geq$ Va.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The first rule ensures that a transaction cannot be committed and aborted at the same time.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The next two rules indicate the votes that a transaction has to obtain before it can terminate one way or the other.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] In replicated databases, a data object has copies present at several sites.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] To ensure serializability, no two transactions should be allowed to read or write a data item concurrently.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] In case of replicated databases, a quorum-based replica control protocol can be used to ensure that no two copies of a data item are read or written by two transactions concurrently.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The quorum-based voting for replica control is due to [Gifford, 1979].
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Each copy of a replicated data item is assigned a vote.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Each operation then has to obtain a *read quorum* (Vr) or a *write quorum* (Vw) to read or write a data item, respectively.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The first rule ensures that a data item is not read and written by two transactions concurrently.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] Additionally, it ensures that a read quorum contains at least one site with the newest version of the data item.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The second rule ensures that two write operations from two transactions cannot occur concurrently on the same data item.
[src:dynamodb/quorum-distributed-computing] The two rules ensure that one-copy serializability is maintained.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] A **vector clock** is a data structure used for determining the partial ordering of events in a distributed system and detecting causality violations.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] Just as in Lamport timestamps, inter-process messages contain the state of the sending process's logical clock.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] A vector clock of a system of *n* processes is a vector (equivalentlly, a 1-dimensional array) of *n* logical clocks, one clock per process.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] Besides maintaining its own clock, every process also keeps track of the largest value of each of the other processes' clocks that it has so far been informed of.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] Lamport originated the idea of logical Lamport clocks in 1978.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] However, the logical clocks in that paper were scalars, not vectors.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] The generalization to vector time was developed several times, apparently independently, by different authors in the early 1980s.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] The papers canonically cited in reference to vector clocks are Colin Fidge’s and Friedemann Mattern’s 1988 works, as they (independently) established the name "vector clock" and the mathematical properties of vector clocks.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] Vector clocks allow for the partial causal ordering of events.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] Vector clocks can reliably detect causality in distributed systems subject to crash failures.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] However, when processes behave arbitrarily or maliciously—as in the Byzantine failure model—causality detection becomes fundamentally impossible , rendering vector clocks ineffective in such environments.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] This impossibility result holds for all variants of vector clocks, as it stems from core limitations inherent to the problem of causality detection under Byzantine faults.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] Modern distributed systems utilize variations of vector clocks to enforce causal ordering of transactions without relying on a central wall-clock time.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] For instance, the Cerberus protocol uses logical clocks to track the state "version" of each shard.
[src:dynamodb/vector-clock] When a transaction spans multiple shards, the vector of these logical clocks allows the network to validate that the transaction is interacting with the most current state of all involved assets, enabling atomic composability in an adversarial environment.
